  "prompt": "What is periodic function?",
  "response": "A **periodic function** is a function that repeats its values at regular intervals or periods. Mathematically, a function \\( f(x) \\) is said to be periodic with period \\( T \\) (where \\( T > 0 \\)) if, for all \\( x \\) in the domain of \\( f \\), the following condition holds:\n\n\\[\nf(x + T) = f(x)\n\\]\n\nThis means that the shape of the function repeats every \\( T \\) units along the \\( x \\)-axis. The smallest positive value of \\( T \\) for which this condition is true is called the **fundamental period** of the function.\n\n### Key Properties of Periodic Functions:\n1. **Repetition:** The function repeats its pattern over every interval of length \\( T \\).\n2. **Period \\( T \\):** The smallest positive number \\( T \\) for which \\( f(x + T) = f(x) \\) holds.\n3. **Graphical Representation:** The graph of a periodic function exhibits symmetry and repeats its shape over regular intervals.\n\n### Examples of Periodic Functions:\n1. **Sine and Cosine Functions:**\n   - \\( \\sin(x) \\) and \\( \\cos(x) \\) are periodic with fundamental period \\( 2\\pi \\), because:\n     \\[\n     \\sin(x + 2\\pi) = \\sin(x) \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\cos(x + 2\\pi) = \\cos(x).\n     \\]\n2. **Square Wave Function:**\n   - A square wave repeats its pattern every \\( T \\) units.\n3. **Sawtooth Wave Function:**\n   - A sawtooth wave also exhibits periodicity with a specific period \\( T \\).\n\n### Applications:\nPeriodic functions are widely used in various fields, including:\n- Signal processing (e.g., sound waves, radio waves).\n- Physics (e.g., oscillations, waves).\n- Engineering (e.g., alternating current, vibrations).\n- Mathematics (e.g., Fourier series, harmonic analysis).\n\nIn summary, a periodic function is a function that exhibits repetition over a specific interval, making it a fundamental concept in mathematics and its applications.",
